  "chunk_index": 8,
  "summary": "Bondel discusses the death of Gerry Wade with Lord Cuttle, discovering that Lanlan Wade is not Gerry's biological sister. Although they share the Wade surname, Lanlan is the child of the late Mr. Wade's second wife, who adopted the name at his insistence. Realizing that Gerry's letter to Lanlan was unusual, Bondel decides she must find Jimmy Sycamore and speak with Lorraine Wade, believing Lorraine may possess clues regarding a \"seven-faced clock\" and an ominous message Gerry left her.\n\nThe following morning, Bondel calls Bill to inquire about Jimmy Sycamore. Bill describes Jimmy as a smart but idle man with a rosy face. During the conversation, Bill mentions Ronnie DeVille, Gerry's best friend, noting that he has not seen him since the weekend Gerry died. Bondel realizes Bill is unaware of Ronnie's death and suspects the police may have covered up the news since it was not reported in the newspapers. Deciding not to tell Bill the truth over the phone, she agrees to meet him for dinner the next evening.\n\nBill provides Jimmy's address at 103 Jemming Street. Upon arriving, Bondel is met by a polite, expressionless man who leads her to a living room. There, she encounters a petite girl in a black dress. Recognizing the mourning clothes, Bondel asks if the girl is Lorraine Wade. Lorraine confirms her identity and mentions receiving a letter from Bondel regarding Gerry. When Bondel asks about Ronnie DeVille, Lorraine reveals she already knows he is dead. After Bondel recounts the recent events, a terrified Lorraine concludes that Gerry Wade did not die naturally but was murdered.",
